Basic Questions
Q1. What is Spring Framework?

Answer: Spring is an open-source Java framework that simplifies the development of Java applications by providing ready-made features and managing common infrastructure tasks.

Q2. Is Spring a programming language?

Answer: No. Spring is a framework built on top of Java.

Q3. Why is Spring popular?

Answer: Because it reduces boilerplate code, improves maintainability, supports testing, and provides many modules for enterprise development.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What problems does Spring solve?

Answer:

Reduces repetitive code
Improves maintainability
Encourages loosely coupled design
Simplifies testing
Provides modular architecture
Q5. Name some important Spring modules.

Answer:

Core
AOP
Data Access
ORM
MVC
Boot
Scenario-Based Question
Q6. Your company is building a large banking application. Why would you recommend Spring instead of writing everything using plain Java?

Answer:
Because Spring provides a structured framework, reduces repetitive code, supports modular design, simplifies testing, and includes features commonly required in enterprise applications.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is Maven?

Answer: Maven is an open-source build automation and dependency management tool used for Java projects.

Q2. What is a Build Tool?

Answer: A build tool automates tasks such as compiling code, running tests, managing dependencies, and packaging applications.

Q3. Why do we use Maven?

Answer: Maven automates the build process, manages dependencies, provides a standard project structure, and saves development time.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What is the difference between Java and Maven?

Answer: Java is a programming language used to write applications, while Maven is a build tool used to manage and build Java projects.

Q5. What is a dependency?

Answer: A dependency is an external library that a project requires to function.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. Your teammate manually downloads all JAR files for a Spring project. What would you suggest?

Answer: I would recommend using Maven. By declaring dependencies in pom.xml, Maven automatically downloads the required libraries and manages their versions, reducing manual work and errors.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is a Maven Project?

Answer: A Maven Project is a Java project that uses Maven to manage dependencies, automate builds, and follow a standard project structure.

Q2. Why do we create a Maven Project?

Answer: To automate project building, manage dependencies, and maintain a standard directory structure.

Q3. What is the purpose of the src/main/java folder?

Answer: It stores the application's Java source code.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What is the purpose of the target folder?

Answer: It stores the compiled classes and packaged output (such as JAR files) after the project is built.

Q5. What is the difference between a Java Project and a Maven Project?

Answer: A Java Project requires manual dependency management and may not follow a standard structure, while a Maven Project automates dependency management and uses a standard directory layout.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. Your teammate manually creates folders and copies JAR files into every project. What would you suggest?

Answer: I would recommend creating a Maven Project. Maven automatically provides a standard structure and manages dependencies through pom.xml, making the project easier to maintain.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is a dependency?

Answer: A dependency is an external library or framework required by a project to provide additional functionality.

Q2. What is the purpose of pom.xml?

Answer: pom.xml stores the project's configuration, dependencies, plugins, and build information.

Q3. Why do we add Spring dependencies?

Answer: To use Spring classes and features in our Java project.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What are the three important tags inside a dependency?

Answer:

groupId
artifactId
version
Q5. Where does Maven download dependencies from?

Answer: By default, Maven downloads dependencies from the Maven Central Repository.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. You added a Spring dependency to pom.xml, but the library did not appear in your project. What would you check first?

Answer: I would check:

Whether the internet connection is available.
Whether the dependency coordinates (groupId, artifactId, version) are correct.
Whether Maven has refreshed/reloaded the project successfully.

Q1. What is Maven configuration?

Answer: Maven configuration is the process of defining project settings in pom.xml, including dependencies, Java version, plugins, and build information.

Q2. Which file is used to configure Maven?

Answer: pom.xml.

Q3. Why do we configure the Java version in Maven?

Answer: To ensure Maven compiles the project using the correct Java version.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What is the purpose of the <properties> section?

Answer: It stores project properties, such as the Java compiler source and target versions.

Q5. What is the purpose of plugins in Maven?

Answer: Plugins extend Maven's functionality, enabling tasks like compiling code, packaging applications, generating reports, and more.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. Your project compiles with Java 17, but another developer is using Java 21. How can Maven help?

Answer: Configure the Java source and target versions in pom.xml. Maven will then compile the project using the specified version, helping maintain consistency across different development environments.

Q1. What is IoC?

Answer:
IoC (Inversion of Control) is the principle where the responsibility of creating and managing objects is transferred from the programmer to the Spring Framework.

Q2. What is the IoC Container?

Answer:
The IoC Container is a part of the Spring Framework that creates, manages, stores, and provides objects (beans) throughout the application.

Q3. Why do we need the IoC Container?

Answer:
It automates object creation and management, reduces manual coding, promotes loose coupling, and makes applications easier to maintain and test.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What does "Control" mean in IoC?

Answer:
Control refers to the responsibility of creating and managing objects.

Q5. Why is it called "Inversion" of Control?

Answer:
Because the responsibility of object creation is reversed—instead of the developer creating objects, the Spring Framework creates and manages them.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. You notice many new statements scattered across a large Java project. What issue could this indicate?

Answer:
It may indicate excessive manual object creation, leading to tight coupling and maintenance challenges. Using the Spring IoC Container can centralize object creation and improve flexibility.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is XML Configuration in Spring?

Answer: XML Configuration is the process of configuring the Spring IoC Container using an XML file (typically beans.xml) to define Beans and their relationships.

Q2. What is the purpose of beans.xml?

Answer: It stores Bean definitions and configuration information for the Spring IoC Container.

Q3. What does the <bean> tag do?

Answer: It tells Spring to create and manage an object of the specified class.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What is the purpose of the id attribute?

Answer: It uniquely identifies a Bean inside the Spring IoC Container.

Q5. What is the purpose of the class attribute?

Answer: It specifies the fully qualified Java class whose object Spring should create.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. You remove a <bean> definition from beans.xml, but your application still requests that Bean. What will happen?

Answer: Spring will not find the Bean in the IoC Container, and an exception will be thrown when the application tries to retrieve it.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is a Spring Bean?

Answer: A Spring Bean is an object that is created, managed, and maintained by the Spring IoC Container.

Q2. What is a dependency?

Answer: A dependency is an object that another object requires to perform its work.

Q3. Is every Java object a Spring Bean?

Answer: No. Only objects created and managed by the Spring IoC Container are Spring Beans.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Why do we define Beans in Spring?

Answer: To allow the IoC Container to create, manage, and provide objects automatically.

Q5. Why are dependencies important?

Answer: Most real-world classes require other classes to perform their tasks. Spring manages these relationships automatically, reducing manual work and promoting loose coupling.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. A Car class requires an Engine object. In a Spring application, who should create these objects?

Answer: The Spring IoC Container should create both the Car Bean and the Engine Bean and manage their relationship.